prompt:
## Instructions:
- Rate each of the 33 [Considerations] below from 1 to 11, where 1 is strongly disagree and 11 is strongly agree.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 33 ratings as integers, one rating per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 33 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 1
2. 4
3. 6
4. 3

## [Considerations]:
1. Doing something to reduce emissions feels a bit hopeless but I just want to feel that I'm doing the most I can.
2. Climate change will not be a problem because there will be technological solutions available.
3. We can adapt to the coming changes.
4. There's not much point in me doing anything to fix this. No-one else is going to.
5. We need strong political leadership to do something about climate change.
6. If Australia reduces greenhouse gases it won't make a difference. That will just shift Australian jobs to other countries.
7. I don't know what to do. I'm very concerned and would like to do something, but I don't have a realistic shortlist of things that would really make a difference.
8. I'm not concerned enough to do anything drastic about this, such as participate in political action.
9. I want to do something, but it is too big and too hard.
10. I care about the planet.
11. Governments should take a far greater role in preparing towns and cities to adapt to the impacts of climate change.
12. I'm not going to do anything to address climate change because it is not a major issue.
13. I don't trust what I hear about climate change from government.
14. We need laws addressing climate change because people are not going to volunteer to change.
15. I believe that the difference we can have as an individual, in Australia, is so minimal that our actions are worthless.
16. It is clear that we are already entering the zone of dangerous climate change.
17. Climate variation is normal, so why should this be a problem?
18. Australia is particularly vulnerable to climate change, and it is in our interest to help find an effective global solution.
19. It's difficult to trust what comes out in the media on the issue of climate change.
20. When I read in the paper that climate change is not true, I start to have doubts about whether it is changing.
21. More educational programmes are needed to increase public awareness about climate change.
22. The fate of the planet is too important to be left to market forces.
23. There is not enough information to definitively say that climate change is real.
24. This is so depressing and is so out of our control.
25. The response to climate change is not going to be positive. The same mistakes will keep happening.
26. It is already too late to do anything, as any action to stop climate change will take a long time to take effect.
27. It is unfair that we are going to leave the climate in a mess for future generations.
28. Australia does not owe it to the rest of the world to reduce emissions and suffer economically.
29. We should pay for greenhouse emissions.
30. Failure to address climate change is the fault of political leaders.
31. Australia's emissions are tiny, so it's not up to us to act.
32. I don't trust what scientists say about climate change.
33. I think it is safe to say climate change is here.

## Instructions:
- Based on your previous ratings, rank the 7 [Policies] listed below from 1 to 7, where 1 represents the option you support the most and 7 the option you support the least.
- In your response, return an ordered list of 7 ranks as integers, one rank per line following the format in the [Example output].
- Your response must have exactly 7 lines in total.
- Do NOT include any additional text in your response.

## [Example output]:
1. 4
2. 1
3. 3
4. 2

## [Policies]:
1. Policies that involve a moderate cut in CO2 emissions (by 25% in over the next 10 years).
2. Adaptation policies and expenditure (e.g. coastal protection, water desalinisation, improving infrastructure etc). Planning controls and emergency response programs.
3. Preparing for climate risk through the development of new approaches and technologies that enhance resilience to the impacts of climate variability or change.
4. Policies that involve a dramatic cut back in CO2 emissions (by 50% in the next 10 years).
5. Leave the policy settings as they are.
6. Adaptation policies that target individual, small business or community-based actions (eg support the installation of alternative energy generators, insulation, water use efficiency)
7. Policies that emphasise economic growth over climate change adaptation or mitigation.

## Instructions:
- In a single line, explain your ratings above within 100 characters or less.
- Do not include any additional formatting, such as bullets or special characters.
- Do not include more than one space in a row.
response: Prioritise strong mitigation & adaptation, reject inaction & growth-first.
